{"title_page": "Portugal\u2013Spain border", "text_new": "{{Infobox border\n | name = Portugal\u2013Spain border\n | image = Puente Internacional 416.jpg\n | alt =\n | caption = [[Guadiana International Bridge]], connecting Portugal and Spain\n | territory1 ={{POR}}\n | territory2 ={{ESP}}\n | length = 1214 km (Claimed by Portugal) / 1232 km (Claimed by Spain)\n | enclaves =\n | established = 1143\n | establishedreason = The victory of king [[Afonso I of Portugal]] over his cousin king [[Alfonso VII of Le\u00f3n]] at the [[Battle of Valdevez]], forced the [[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n]] to recognise [[Portugal]] as a country, thus establishing the northern borders of Portugal. \n | current = \n | currentreason = \n | disestablished =\n | disestablishedreason =\n | treaties = * [[Treaty of Zamora (1143)]]\n* [[Treaty of Badajoz (1267)]]\n* [[Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices (1297)]] \n* [[Treaty of Badajoz (1801)]] \n* [[Congress of Vienna (1815)]] \n* [[Treaty of Lisbon (1864)]] \n* [[Convention of Limits (1926)]]\n | notes = \n}}\n\nThe '''Portugal\u2013Spain border''' is referred to as \"'''The Stripe'''\" ({{lang-gl|A Raia}}, {{lang-pt|A Raia}}, {{lang-mwl|La Raia}}, {{lang-es|La Raya}}). The current demarcation is almost identical to that defined in 1297 by the [[Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices (1297)|Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices]]. It is one of the oldest borders in the world. The Portugal\u2013Spain border is {{convert|1214|km|abbr=on}} long, and considered the longest uninterrupted border within the [[European Union]]. The border is not defined for {{convert|18|km|abbr=on}} between the [[Caia (river)|Caia river]] and [[Ribeira de Cuncos]], because of the disputed status of [[Olivenza|Olivenza/Oliven\u00e7a]], which has been disputed between the two countries for two hundred years.\n\nA microstate existed previously on the border called [[Couto Misto]].\n\n==Bordering districts and provinces==\n[[File:Traffic sign of border with Portugal.svg|thumbnail|200px|Sign when entering Portugal from Spain.]]\n[[File:Traffic sign of border with Spain.svg|thumbnail|200px|Sign when entering Spain from Portugal.]]\n\nDistricts on the Portuguese side of the border from North to South:\n*[[File:VCT.png|20px]] [[Viana do Castelo District]] ([[Northern Portugal]])\n*[[File:BRG.png|20px]] [[Braga District]] (Northern Portugal)\n*[[File:VRL.png|20px]] [[Vila Real District]] (Northern Portugal)\n*[[File:Bras\u00e3o de Bragan\u00e7a.png|20px]] [[Bragan\u00e7a District]] (Northern Portugal)\n*[[File:GRD.png|20px]] [[Guarda District]] ([[Central Portugal]])\n*[[File:CTB.png|20px]] [[Castelo Branco District]] (Central Portugal)\n*[[File:PTG.png|20px]] [[Portalegre District]] ([[Alentejo Region|Alentejo]])\n*[[File:COA of \u00c9vora municipality (Portugal).png|20px]] [[\u00c9vora District]] (Alentejo)\n*[[File:BJA.png|20px]] [[Beja District]] (Alentejo)\n*[[File:FAR.png|20px]] [[Faro District]] ([[Algarve]])\n\nProvinces on the Spanish side of the border from North to South:\n*[[Province of Pontevedra]] ([[File:Flag of Galicia.svg|25px]] [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]])\n*[[Province of Ourense]] ([[File:Flag of Galicia.svg|25px]] [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]])\n*[[Province of Zamora]] ([[File:Flag_of_Castile_and_Le\u00f3n.svg|25px]] [[Castile and Le\u00f3n]])\n*[[Province of Salamanca]] ([[File:Flag_of_Castile_and_Le\u00f3n.svg|25px]] [[Castile and Le\u00f3n]])\n*[[Province of C\u00e1ceres]] ([[File:Flag of Extremadura.svg|25px]] [[Extremadura]])\n*[[Province of Badajoz]] ([[File:Flag of Extremadura.svg|25px]] [[Extremadura]])\n*[[Province of Huelva]] ([[File:Bandera de Andaluc\u00eda.svg|25px]] [[Andalusia]])\n\n==Customs and identity checks==\nPortugal and Spain signed the [[Schengen Agreement]] in June 1991 which came into effect on 26 March 1995, making Portugal and Spain part of the [[Schengen area]] and thus the border then became an [[Open border]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url = http://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/e-library/docs/schengen_brochure/schengen_brochure_dr3111126_en.pdf\n | title = The Schengen area - PDF by EU\n | accessdate = 28 April 2017}}\n</ref> \n\nPortugal has since reintroduced border checks several times along the border with Spain, during the [[UEFA Euro 2004]] championships,  during the [[2010 Lisbon summit|NATO 2010 Lisbon summit]] and during [[Pope Francis]]'s visit to [[F\u00e1tima, Portugal|F\u00e1tima]] in May 2017.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url = http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/portugal-declares-papal-holiday/41769\n | title = Portugal declares Papal holiday\n | accessdate = 28 April 2017}}\n</ref>\n\nOn the 16 March 2020 Portugal and Spain reintroduced border checks due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], with tourists unable to cross, but allowing cross border workers and goods to pass.<ref> \n{{cite web\n | url = https://www.thelocal.es/20200317/coronavirus-what-you-need-to-know-about-spain-closing-its-borders\n | title = Coronavirus: What you need to know about Spain closing its borders\n | accessdate = 18 March 2020}}\n</ref>\nThe checks are planned until May 15 2020.<ref> \n{{cite web\n | url = https://www.theportugalnews.com/news/border-with-spain-to-remain-closed/53761\n | title = Border with Spain to remain closed\n | accessdate = 18 April 2020}}\n</ref>\n\n===Border crossing check points===\n*[[Valen\u00e7a, Portugal|Valen\u00e7a]]-[[Tui, Pontevedra|Tui]]\n*[[Vila Verde da Raia]]-[[Ver\u00edn]]\n*[[Quintanilha]]-[[San Vitero]]\n*[[Vilar Formoso]]-[[Fuentes de O\u00f1oro]]\n*[[Termas de Monfortinho]]-[[Cilleros]]\n*[[Marv\u00e3o]]-[[Valencia de Alc\u00e1ntara]]\n*[[Elvas]]-[[Badajoz]]\n*[[Vila Verde de Ficalho]]-[[Rosal de la Frontera]]\n*[[Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio]]-[[Ayamonte]]\n\n==Maritime borders==\nPortugal's maritime borders, also known as the [[Exclusive economic zone of Portugal]] is currently disputed by Spain in the [[Savage Islands]] area, between [[Madeira]] and the [[Canary Islands]].\n\n==Important treaties==\n* [[Treaty of Zamora (1143)]] - The victory of king [[Afonso I of Portugal]] over his cousin king [[Alfonso VII of Le\u00f3n]] at the [[Battle of Valdevez]], forced the [[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n]] to recognise [[Portugal]] as a country, thus establishing the northern borders of Portugal. \n* [[Treaty of Badajoz (1267)]] - Signed by king [[Alfonso X of Castile]] and King [[Afonso III of Portugal]], establishing the [[Guadiana]] as roughly the southern border.\n* [[Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices (1297)]] - Signed by King [[Denis of Portugal]] (grandson of king [[Alfonso X of Castile]]) and King [[Ferdinand IV of Castile]], [[Oliven\u00e7a, Portugal|Oliven\u00e7a]] is ceded to Portugal.\n* [[Treaty of Badajoz (1801)]] - [[Oliven\u00e7a, Portugal|Oliven\u00e7a]] is ceded to Spain.\n* [[Congress of Vienna (1815)]] - Spain promises to return [[Oliven\u00e7a, Portugal|Oliven\u00e7a]] to Portugal, leaving this area of the border disputed ever since.\n* [[Treaty of Lisbon (1864)]] - This abolished the [[Couto Misto]] microstate.\n* [[Convention of Limits (1926)]] - Demarcating the border from the confluence of Ribeira de Cuncos with the Guadiana, just south of Oliven\u00e7a, to the estuary of the Guadiana River, on the far South.\n\n==Border crossings==\n[[File:Fronteira Portugal Espa\u00f1a - panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Vilar Formoso - Fuentes de O\u00f1oro border crossing]]\nThe main crossing point between Portugal and Spain is [[Vilar Formoso]] - [[Fuentes de O\u00f1oro]]. Other important crossings are [[Caminha]] and [[Bragan\u00e7a, Portugal|Bragan\u00e7a]] to [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], [[Portalegre, Portugal|Portalegre]] and [[Elvas]] to [[Badajoz]], and [[Castro Marim]] and [[Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio]] to [[Ayamonte]].\n\nBridges across the border include the [[Guadiana International Bridge]] and the [[Lower Guadiana International bridge]].\n\nThe World's shortest international bridge connects the Portuguese village of V\u00e1rzea Grande ([[Arronches|Arronches municipality]]) with the Spanish village of El Marco ([[La Codosera|La Codosera municipality]]). It is a wooden bridge with only 3.2 meters long.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/the-worlds-shortest-international-bridge-esperanca-portugal |title=The World\u2019s Shortest International Bridge|accessdate=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n\nA [[zipline]] across the border exists between [[Sanlucar de Guadiana]] in Spain and [[Alcoutim]] in Portugal; it is the first and currently only zip line over an international border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/484285/Spain-becomes-homes-to-first-ever-time-travelling-zipline |title=Spain becomes home to world's first-ever 'time-travelling' zipline|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/cross-border-international-zipline_n_5309332?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGltaXRlemVyby5jb20vZW4vbmV3cy8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAAINhph8b-QHpxSe2KHEBtJC7c_R6caBtx32q4xxCJ7SSZn5Zao3L6xTB09kMRFgblp_lCtZhxUWrzWuxlTgB7nVcijOhb6kQqjz_YmODI-swI6JYsBTdXk02kEiGvqDvKi8SX1ZTBXvUs5YLjuCzFvuXzEaU7fRyh1Pbkq3Hat6 |title=Travel From Spain To Portugal In Less Than A Minute With This Zany Zip-Line|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Borders of Spain}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Portugal-Spain border}}\n[[Category:Borders of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Borders of Spain]]\n[[Category:Portugal\u2013Spain border| ]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox border\n | name = Portugal\u2013Spain border\n | image = Puente Internacional 416.jpg\n | alt =\n | caption = [[Guadiana International Bridge]], connecting Portugal and Spain\n | territory1 ={{POR}}\n | territory2 ={{ESP}}\n | length = 1214 km (Claimed by Portugal) / 1232 km (Claimed by Spain)\n | enclaves =\n | established = 1143\n | establishedreason = The victory of king [[Afonso I of Portugal]] over his cousin king [[Alfonso VII of Le\u00f3n]] at the [[Battle of Valdevez]], forced the [[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n]] to recognise [[Portugal]] as a country, thus establishing the northern borders of Portugal. \n | current = \n | currentreason = \n | disestablished =\n | disestablishedreason =\n | treaties = * [[Treaty of Zamora (1143)]]\n* [[Treaty of Badajoz (1267)]]\n* [[Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices (1297)]] \n* [[Treaty of Badajoz (1801)]] \n* [[Congress of Vienna (1815)]] \n* [[Treaty of Lisbon (1864)]] \n* [[Convention of Limits (1926)]]\n | notes = \n}}\n\nThe '''Portugal\u2013Spain border''' is referred to as \"'''The Stripe'''\" ({{lang-gl|A Raia}}, {{lang-pt|A Raia}}, {{lang-mwl|La Raia}}, {{lang-es|La Raya}}). The current demarcation is almost identical to that defined in 1297 by the [[Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices (1297)|Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices]]. It is one of the oldest borders in the world. The Portugal\u2013Spain border is {{convert|1214|km|abbr=on}} long, and considered the longest uninterrupted border within the [[European Union]]. The border is not defined for {{convert|18|km|abbr=on}} between the [[Caia (river)|Caia river]] and [[Ribeira de Cuncos]], because of the disputed status of [[Olivenza|Olivenza/Oliven\u00e7a]], which has been disputed between the two countries for two hundred years.\n\nA microstate existed previously on the border called [[Couto Misto]].\n\n==Bordering districts and provinces==\n[[File:Traffic sign of border with Portugal.svg|thumbnail|200px|Sign when entering Portugal from Spain.]]\n[[File:Traffic sign of border with Spain.svg|thumbnail|200px|Sign when entering Spain from Portugal.]]\n\nDistricts on the Portuguese side of the border from North to South:\n*[[File:VCT.png|20px]] [[Viana do Castelo District]] ([[Northern Portugal]])\n*[[File:BRG.png|20px]] [[Braga District]] (Northern Portugal)\n*[[File:VRL.png|20px]] [[Vila Real District]] (Northern Portugal)\n*[[File:Bras\u00e3o de Bragan\u00e7a.png|20px]] [[Bragan\u00e7a District]] (Northern Portugal)\n*[[File:GRD.png|20px]] [[Guarda District]] ([[Central Portugal]])\n*[[File:CTB.png|20px]] [[Castelo Branco District]] (Central Portugal)\n*[[File:PTG.png|20px]] [[Portalegre District]] ([[Alentejo Region|Alentejo]])\n*[[File:COA of \u00c9vora municipality (Portugal).png|20px]] [[\u00c9vora District]] (Alentejo)\n*[[File:BJA.png|20px]] [[Beja District]] (Alentejo)\n*[[File:FAR.png|20px]] [[Faro District]] ([[Algarve]])\n\nProvinces on the Spanish side of the border from North to South:\n*[[Province of Pontevedra]] ([[File:Flag of Galicia.svg|25px]] [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]])\n*[[Province of Ourense]] ([[File:Flag of Galicia.svg|25px]] [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]])\n*[[Province of Zamora]] ([[File:Flag_of_Castile_and_Le\u00f3n.svg|25px]] [[Castile and Le\u00f3n]])\n*[[Province of Salamanca]] ([[File:Flag_of_Castile_and_Le\u00f3n.svg|25px]] [[Castile and Le\u00f3n]])\n*[[Province of C\u00e1ceres]] ([[File:Flag of Extremadura.svg|25px]] [[Extremadura]])\n*[[Province of Badajoz]] ([[File:Flag of Extremadura.svg|25px]] [[Extremadura]])\n*[[Province of Huelva]] ([[File:Bandera de Andaluc\u00eda.svg|25px]] [[Andalusia]])\n\n==Customs and identity checks==\nPortugal and Spain signed the [[Schengen Agreement]] in June 1991 which came into effect on 26 March 1995, making Portugal and Spain part of the [[Schengen area]] and thus the border then became an [[Open border]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url = http://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/e-library/docs/schengen_brochure/schengen_brochure_dr3111126_en.pdf\n | title = The Schengen area - PDF by EU\n | accessdate = 28 April 2017}}\n</ref> \n\nPortugal has since reintroduced border checks several times along the border with Spain, during the [[UEFA Euro 2004]] championships,  during the [[2010 Lisbon summit|NATO 2010 Lisbon summit]] and during [[Pope Francis]]'s visit to [[F\u00e1tima, Portugal|F\u00e1tima]] in May 2017.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url = http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/portugal-declares-papal-holiday/41769\n | title = Portugal declares Papal holiday\n | accessdate = 28 April 2017}}\n</ref>\n\nOn the 16 March 2020 Portugal and Spain reintroduced border checks due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], with tourists unable to cross, but allowing cross border workers and goods to pass.<ref> \n{{cite web\n | url = https://www.thelocal.es/20200317/coronavirus-what-you-need-to-know-about-spain-closing-its-borders\n | title = Coronavirus: What you need to know about Spain closing its borders\n | accessdate = 18 March 2020}}\n</ref>\nThe checks are planned until May 15 2020.<ref> \n{{cite web\n | url = https://www.theportugalnews.com/news/border-with-spain-to-remain-closed/53761\n | title = Border with Spain to remain closed\n | accessdate = 18 April 2020}}\n</ref>\n\n===Border crossing check points===\n*[[Valen\u00e7a, Portugal|Valen\u00e7a]]-[[Tui, Pontevedra|Tui]]\n*[[Vila Verde da Raia]]-[[Ver\u00edn]]\n*[[Quintanilha]]-[[San Vitero]]\n*[[Vilar Formoso]]-[[Fuentes de O\u00f1oro]]\n*[[Termas de Monfortinho]]-[[Cilleros]]\n*[[Marv\u00e3o]]-[[Valencia de Alc\u00e1ntara]]\n*[[Caia]]-[[Badajoz]]\n*[[Vila Verde de Ficalho]]-[[Rosal de la Frontera]]\n*[[Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio]]-[[Ayamonte]]\n\n==Maritime borders==\nPortugal's maritime borders, also known as the [[Exclusive economic zone of Portugal]] is currently disputed by Spain in the [[Savage Islands]] area, between [[Madeira]] and the [[Canary Islands]].\n\n==Important treaties==\n* [[Treaty of Zamora (1143)]] - The victory of king [[Afonso I of Portugal]] over his cousin king [[Alfonso VII of Le\u00f3n]] at the [[Battle of Valdevez]], forced the [[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n]] to recognise [[Portugal]] as a country, thus establishing the northern borders of Portugal. \n* [[Treaty of Badajoz (1267)]] - Signed by king [[Alfonso X of Castile]] and King [[Afonso III of Portugal]], establishing the [[Guadiana]] as roughly the southern border.\n* [[Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices (1297)]] - Signed by King [[Denis of Portugal]] (grandson of king [[Alfonso X of Castile]]) and King [[Ferdinand IV of Castile]], [[Oliven\u00e7a, Portugal|Oliven\u00e7a]] is ceded to Portugal.\n* [[Treaty of Badajoz (1801)]] - [[Oliven\u00e7a, Portugal|Oliven\u00e7a]] is ceded to Spain.\n* [[Congress of Vienna (1815)]] - Spain promises to return [[Oliven\u00e7a, Portugal|Oliven\u00e7a]] to Portugal, leaving this area of the border disputed ever since.\n* [[Treaty of Lisbon (1864)]] - This abolished the [[Couto Misto]] microstate.\n* [[Convention of Limits (1926)]] - Demarcating the border from the confluence of Ribeira de Cuncos with the Guadiana, just south of Oliven\u00e7a, to the estuary of the Guadiana River, on the far South.\n\n==Border crossings==\n[[File:Fronteira Portugal Espa\u00f1a - panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Vilar Formoso - Fuentes de O\u00f1oro border crossing]]\nThe main crossing point between Portugal and Spain is [[Vilar Formoso]] - [[Fuentes de O\u00f1oro]]. Other important crossings are [[Caminha]] and [[Bragan\u00e7a, Portugal|Bragan\u00e7a]] to [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], [[Portalegre, Portugal|Portalegre]] and [[Elvas]] to [[Badajoz]], and [[Castro Marim]] and [[Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio]] to [[Ayamonte]].\n\nBridges across the border include the [[Guadiana International Bridge]] and the [[Lower Guadiana International bridge]].\n\nThe World's shortest international bridge connects the Portuguese village of V\u00e1rzea Grande ([[Arronches|Arronches municipality]]) with the Spanish village of El Marco ([[La Codosera|La Codosera municipality]]). It is a wooden bridge with only 3.2 meters long.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/the-worlds-shortest-international-bridge-esperanca-portugal |title=The World\u2019s Shortest International Bridge|accessdate=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n\nA [[zipline]] across the border exists between [[Sanlucar de Guadiana]] in Spain and [[Alcoutim]] in Portugal; it is the first and currently only zip line over an international border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/484285/Spain-becomes-homes-to-first-ever-time-travelling-zipline |title=Spain becomes home to world's first-ever 'time-travelling' zipline|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/cross-border-international-zipline_n_5309332?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGltaXRlemVyby5jb20vZW4vbmV3cy8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAAINhph8b-QHpxSe2KHEBtJC7c_R6caBtx32q4xxCJ7SSZn5Zao3L6xTB09kMRFgblp_lCtZhxUWrzWuxlTgB7nVcijOhb6kQqjz_YmODI-swI6JYsBTdXk02kEiGvqDvKi8SX1ZTBXvUs5YLjuCzFvuXzEaU7fRyh1Pbkq3Hat6 |title=Travel From Spain To Portugal In Less Than A Minute With This Zany Zip-Line|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Borders of Spain}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Portugal-Spain border}}\n[[Category:Borders of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Borders of Spain]]\n[[Category:Portugal\u2013Spain border| ]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "name_user": "Rockysantos", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBorder crossing check points", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portugal%E2%80%93Spain_border"}
